snippet.textDisplay:
NOTE: In order for a sanctioning body to name its own world champions and hold world championship bouts, it HAS to be recognized by the IBHOF (International Boxing Hall of Fame).


Lineal Championship: This means that a boxer is the latest in a long line of men who beat the man who beat the man who beat the original heavyweight champion of the world. For example, the first world recognized heavyweight champion was an Irish-American named John L. Sullivan, when he beat Jake Kilrain in he 75th round of an 80 round bout. From there, he was beaten by James J. Corbett, who became the next heavyweight champion. This continued from man to man, regardless of any additional belts added to the boxing world, until Tyson Fury defeated Wladimir Klitschko, thus becoming the latest lineal heavyweight champion of the world.


IBF (International Boxing Federation): Created in New Jersey where its headquarters still remain, it was formed by Robert W. Lee Sr. in 1977, but wasn't recognized as a world wide sanctioning body by the IBHOF until 1983. Its current president is Daryl Peoples.


WBA (World Boxing Association): Created in the United States, it is the oldest of the sanctioning bodies, and was renamed in 1962 after going by the name of NBA (National Boxing Association) since 1921. By 1975, the headquarters of the WBA where moved to Panama, where it remains today. Its current president is Gilberto Mendoza. If a boxer has both the WBA and one other championship belt, then he is named the "Super" champion, and two other contenders fight for the right to be called the "Regular" WBA champion. Because of this, there CAN exist TWO WBA champions in any weight class.


WBC (World Boxing Council): The most prestigious of all sanctioning bodies, the WBC was formed in 1963. There are 161 flags on its green belt, each representing a country who's membership belongs with the WBC, and is thus eligible to have a champion. Its president is Mauricio Sulaiman, and its headquarters are located in Mexico City. The WBC has FOUR different championships. 1) Diamond Belt: Given to the winner of a historic championship fight 2) Silver Belt: Given as a secondary belt, on top of the traditional green belt. 3) Eternal Championship: Given to champions who retire undefeated after becoming champion. 4) Green Belt: The traditional WBC world champion award.


WBO (World Boxing Organization): The youngest of the major sanctioning bodies, it was founded in 1988, but wasn't recognized by the IBHOF until 2004. Its president is Francisco Varcarcel, and its headquarters are located in San Juan, Puerto Rico.
